# Day 12: Geolocation from Images

## Introduction
Day 12 of my 30 Days of OSINT (Open Source Intelligence) Challenge.

Today, I explored Geolocation from Images, one of the most fascinating and practical techniques in Open Source Intelligence (OSINT). 
It is the process of identifying where a photograph was taken by analyzing the visual clues present in the image and comparing them with publicly available information.
Unlike Metadata Analysis (EXIF), geolocation does not depend on hidden GPS information stored inside a file. Instead,
it relies on observation, logical thinking, and verification. Every image contains visible clues that can help narrow down its location if analyzed carefully.
One of the biggest lessons from today's learning is that an investigator doesn't need to know the answer
immediately—they need to know how to observe, question, and verify every clue.


